ğŸŒ Program 7 â€” Part B: Hosting a Static Website on S3
âœ… STEP 1: Prepare Your Website Files
You need:

index.html (mandatory)

Optional: CSS, JS, images, etc.

Example: Create a basic index.html
On your desktop:

Open Notepad or VS Code

Paste this:

html
Copy
Edit
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My S3 Website</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Hello from AWS S3! ğŸŒ</h1>
</body>
</html>
Save the file as index.html

âœ… STEP 2: Create a New S3 Bucket
Go to https://s3.console.aws.amazon.com/s3

Click Create bucket

Fill the form:
Bucket name: e.g., nimra-s3-static-site (must be globally unique)

Region: Keep as Asia Pacific (Mumbai) ap-south-1 or your preferred

Uncheck: Block all public access âœ…

Scroll down â†’ Click Create bucket

âœ… STEP 3: Upload Website Files
Click on your bucket name

Go to the Objects tab

Click Upload

Click Add files â†’ Select index.html (and other folders if you have CSS/JS)

Click Upload

âœ… STEP 4: Enable Static Website Hosting
Go to the Properties tab of your bucket

Scroll down to Static website hosting

Click Edit

Choose Enable

Index document: index.html

Error document (optional): error.html

Click Save changes

âœ… Youâ€™ll now see the Website endpoint URL

Example: http://nimra-s3-static-site.s3-website.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

But wait... it's still blocked! Now we allow public access ğŸ‘‡

âœ… STEP 5: Set Bucket Policy to Allow Public Access
Go to the Permissions tab of the bucket

Scroll to Bucket policy

Click Edit

Paste this policy (replace your-bucket-name with your actual bucket name):

json
Copy
Edit
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicReadAccess",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::your-bucket-name/*"
    }
  ]
}
ğŸ“Œ Example for nimra-s3-static-site:

json
Copy
Edit
"Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::nimra-s3-static-site/*"
Click Save changes

âœ… STEP 6: Open Your Website ğŸ‰
Go back to the Properties tab

Scroll to Static website hosting

Copy the Website endpoint URL

Paste it in a new browser tab

You should now see your static site live from S3!
